# 8-10 Minute Presentation Script

Good day everyone. My individual coursework project is titled **Transformer Fault Diagnosis ML Methods Classification**.

The purpose of this project is to reorganize a machine-learning workflow into a proper Python repository. My dataset contains Scopus records related to power-transformer fault diagnosis and dissolved gas analysis. Each record includes a title, year, abstract, keywords, and an extracted summary of the machine-learning methods mentioned in the paper.

First, I checked the dataset and found that the `Screening decision` column contains only one class, which is `Keep`. Since a model cannot learn a useful classifier from only one class, I created a more meaningful target variable called `target_category`. This target is derived from the first extracted machine-learning method category in the `output abstract extraction` column.

The workflow starts in `main.py`. This file connects every module together. The first module is `data_loader.py`, where I created a `DatasetLoader` class to load the Excel file and validate the important columns. This improves reliability because the program will stop early if required columns are missing.

Next is the preprocessing stage. In `preprocessing.py`, the `MethodExtractionParser` parses the JSON-like extraction column, while `TransformerFaultPreprocessor` cleans missing text, combines the title, abstract, and keywords, and creates the target category. I also normalised similar method categories into broader groups such as Neural Network / Deep Learning, Ensemble Learning, Supervised Learning, Optimization, and Statistical / Feature Methods.

For feature engineering, I used TF-IDF. This converts text into numeric features based on word importance. In `feature_engineering.py`, I used an abstract base class called `TextFeatureBuilder` and an inherited class called `TfidfFeatureBuilder`. This demonstrates abstraction and inheritance.

For model training, I used Linear SVM because it is suitable for text classification with TF-IDF features and is easy to explain. In `train_model.py`, I created a base trainer class and an inherited classifier trainer. The model splits the dataset into training and testing sets, trains the classifier, and predicts the target category.

For evaluation, `evaluate.py` calculates accuracy, macro F1-score, weighted F1-score, classification report, and confusion matrix. The project also saves visual outputs, including publication trend by year, category distribution, top extracted methods, and confusion matrix.

For testing, I created unit tests inside the `tests` folder. These tests check data loading, preprocessing, feature engineering, model training, and evaluation. This helps prove that the code is reliable and modular.

In terms of object-oriented programming, this project uses classes such as `DatasetLoader`, `TransformerFaultPreprocessor`, and `MLCategoryClassifierTrainer`. It uses abstraction through the base classes, inheritance through the TF-IDF feature builder and classifier trainer, and encapsulation because each class keeps related logic together.

To run the project, the user only needs to install the requirements, run `python main.py`, and then run `pytest`. The project is also prepared with a `.devcontainer` folder so it can run in GitHub Codespaces.

In conclusion, this project takes a raw research dataset and turns it into a structured, modular machine-learning repository with preprocessing, training, evaluation, visualization, testing, and documentation.
